// Regression test: passing a generic function call directly as an argument
// to another call (nested generic calls) must resolve the inner call's
// concrete return type, not the raw generic placeholder. Root cause was
// ast_to_fir.py's _expr_type() trusting a stale, unsubstituted
// node.return_type annotation ("T") for a cross-module generic call whose
// defining module wasn't merged yet when the call site was first
// type-checked, which then poisoned println's own generic type-arg
// inference.
import @firescript/std.io.println;
import @firescript/std.math.max;

println(max(3, 7));

/* EXPECT
7
*/
